							<p>The blow horn rang with a defining sound indicating that the team portion of practice was commencing.  As we huddled up to take on the starting offense, we noticed we were one player short. Off in the distance, you could see number 21 moseying toward the huddle. Wearing a black wrist watch with his gloves hanging off of his face mask, Charles Woodson looked more like we were participating in a pre-practice walk-through than a full speed scrimmage.

	 						<p>As we practiced, Charles would do just enough to stay with the receiver. If his guy caught the ball, he wouldn’t even make an attempt to break up the pass. In film study, Woodson’s practice habits almost caused our coaches to lose their minds. But, what kept them from ripping into Charles was that they knew when the game lights were on, this guy flat out dominated. He played at a Hall of Fame level.

	 						<p>Woodson’s practice habits upset the coaches for two reasons.  First, it took the wind out of their sails as they preached “How you practice is how you will play.”  Secondly, our younger players, such as future all-pro safety Nick Collins, started to acquire those same habits. 

	 						<p>Collins, though physically gifted in his own right, could not pull off what Woodson did.   He couldn’t just “turn it on” for the games.  Charles saw the influence he was having on the other players who were beginning to struggle. He decided to change the way he practiced. Charles, along with other veterans in the defensive backfield, began competing to see who could make the most interceptions.

	 						<p>Charles took this competition seriously. Whether it was practice or games, he loved to use the bait-and-hook method to pick off passes. Charles would make it seem like the receiver was open and then use his quickness to sneak in front at the last second for a pick. He did this time and time again.

	 						<p><a href="http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-game-highlights/0ap3000000390280/Woodson-intercepts-Geno-Smith" target="_blank">Watch Video: NY Jets QB Geno Smith was baited-and-hooked this last weekend by the old savvy vet</a>.

	 						<p>Woodson now practiced and played in games like a Hall of Famer.  The younger guys like Nick Collins and Tramon Williams elevated their play to All-Pro/Pro Bowl levels.  These young bucks learned that not many are as talented as Charles Woodson. 

							<p>In reality, Charles is an exception to the rule that “you will practice how you will play in a game”.  He was not the norm.  He was one in a billion. He was the best football player I ever player with.
							
						</div>
